WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.400
So I will not be talking about a VTK degrader.

00:00:03.420 --> 00:00:07.680
So I'm going to be talking about goldcadamide in the role of, which is a cell mod in combination

00:00:07.680 --> 00:00:11.120
with rituximab in patients with relapse, refractory, diffuse-sorged basal lymphoma.

00:00:13.020 --> 00:00:17.620
So as we know, in the current era, approximately two-thirds of patients with newly diagnosed

00:00:17.620 --> 00:00:20.640
diffuse-sorged basal lymphoma will be able to achieve cure with chemoimmunotherapy.

00:00:21.280 --> 00:00:24.740
Unfortunately, that means that approximately 30% to 40% of patients will experience relapse

00:00:24.740 --> 00:00:25.900
or refractory disease.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:31.280
While effective treatment options are becoming more widely available, some of these are still

00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:33.460
limited by access to them or patient fitness.

00:00:33.880 --> 00:00:36.540
So there's still an area of unmet need for these patients with refractory disease.

00:00:37.360 --> 00:00:41.620
Goldcadamide is an investigational potential forced-in-class oral small molecule cell mod

00:00:41.620 --> 00:00:46.220
agent, which we've heard about earlier in this meeting, which is designed for the treatment

00:00:46.220 --> 00:00:46.800
of lymphoma.

00:00:47.880 --> 00:00:52.300
So goldcadamide's role in the treatment of relapse, refractory, diffuse-sorged basal

00:00:52.300 --> 00:00:56.200
lymphoma was studied in a Phase I-II study.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.400
This study was done in 2009-2002, which we have some recent data updates presented at

00:01:00.400 --> 00:01:02.540
ASH by Hoffman et al., which I'm going to go over.

00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:09.200
So we've heard of the cell mod mechanism of action from some of the earlier multiple myeloma

00:01:09.200 --> 00:01:09.720
talks.

00:01:11.300 --> 00:01:15.680
You know, it shares a similar mechanism to mizictamide, so I'm not going to go over too

00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:22.520
much of the details, but a similar mechanism of action is that it binds to cereblon and

00:01:22.520 --> 00:01:26.680
causes it to favor the closed active conformation.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:32.360
Which leads to increased IKROS and IOLOS degradation via the proteasome pathway.

00:01:32.360 --> 00:01:37.200
Where it differs from some of the multiple myeloma cell mods is that it does have a preferential

00:01:37.200 --> 00:01:43.640
viability in the lymphoid organs, which makes it an attractive option for its use in lymphoma.

00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:53.320
So CC99282 was a Phase I-II multicenter study using goldcadamide as its monotherapy and

00:01:53.320 --> 00:01:56.560
later in combination with rituximab in patients with relapse, refractory, non-hostile disease.

00:01:56.560 --> 00:02:03.240
You can see here the study schema, Part A being the dose escalation, where they were

00:02:03.240 --> 00:02:05.560
able to select the schedule and the dose.

00:02:05.560 --> 00:02:09.560
I'm going to be mostly focusing on the updated data from Cohort C, which is highlighted there

00:02:09.560 --> 00:02:14.600
in the green box, which included both dose of 0.2 and 0.4 milligrams of goldcadamide in

00:02:14.600 --> 00:02:15.800
combination with rituximab.

00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:19.320
And you can see the primary objectives and secondary objectives report on the right.

00:02:22.440 --> 00:02:26.120
So for in this cohort that included the two different doses, you can see some of the different

00:02:26.120 --> 00:02:27.120
characteristics.

00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:28.120
You can see some of the patient characteristics here.

00:02:28.120 --> 00:02:33.000
So generally, this was a pretty heavily pre-treated population with a median prior lines of therapy

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:37.960
of 4 to 5, with some patients, as you can see, they're receiving even up to 11 prior

00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:39.780
lines of therapy.

00:02:39.780 --> 00:02:44.920
These also included or like over half of patients received some form of T-cell redirecting therapy,

00:02:44.920 --> 00:02:50.040
whether that was a Bispecific or CAR-T, and approximately a quarter in both

00:02:50.040 --> 00:02:55.040
of these arms had received some prior lenalidomide therapy.

00:02:55.040 --> 00:02:56.040
Also of note.

00:02:56.040 --> 00:02:58.600
You can catch on the bottom part of the box there that there were some patients that had

00:02:58.600 --> 00:03:01.040
primary refractory disease with the last line of therapy.

00:03:01.040 --> 00:03:04.760
So you can kind of imagine that these were pretty difficult to or patients with pretty

00:03:04.760 --> 00:03:05.760
aggressive disease.

00:03:05.760 --> 00:03:10.400
Here is the latest patient disposition update from Cohort C.

00:03:10.400 --> 00:03:13.800
So a total of 77 patients were enrolled.

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:18.420
It appears a bit discouraging in the sense that 65% of the patients ultimately came off

00:03:18.420 --> 00:03:23.700
the study, with six patients being able to achieve a durable response and six patients

00:03:23.700 --> 00:03:25.480
being able to complete the plan.

00:03:25.480 --> 00:03:26.040
Two years.

00:03:26.040 --> 00:03:33.040
I'm going to go over some of the complete and overall response data, which shows why

00:03:33.040 --> 00:03:35.800
it still potentially has promise.

00:03:35.800 --> 00:03:41.960
Going over the treatment adverse events, as we know, hematologic toxicity is a known side

00:03:41.960 --> 00:03:44.200
effect from cell mods.

00:03:44.200 --> 00:03:49.540
In particular, with glucatamide, there seemed to be a dose-dependent toxicity with the

00:03:49.540 --> 00:03:54.320
higher doses resulting in an increased risk of severe neutropenia, approximately 80%,

00:03:54.320 --> 00:03:55.960
as well as an increased risk of febrile neutropenia.

00:03:55.960 --> 00:04:01.220
Notably because this shares some mechanisms with IMiDS, there was an interest in seeing

00:04:01.220 --> 00:04:05.640
how many VTEs, or sorry, thrombotic events were present.

00:04:05.640 --> 00:04:09.340
And they did not seem to be very common.

00:04:09.340 --> 00:04:11.620
Thrombobolic prophylaxis was not required in the study.

00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:16.220
So a total of three patients did have a VTE.

00:04:16.220 --> 00:04:20.200
For some of the later phase three studies I'll touch upon in my conclusion, they do

00:04:20.200 --> 00:04:25.280
require VTE prophylaxis just because of the increased risk.

00:04:25.960 --> 00:04:34.260
So, you know, with regards to the overall response and complete response, you can see

00:04:34.260 --> 00:04:39.680
here that in this pretty heavily pre-treated population, on the left includes the overall

00:04:39.680 --> 00:04:42.720
response by dose level, and you can see that the higher dose level was associated with

00:04:42.720 --> 00:04:45.660
a much higher overall response rate.

00:04:45.660 --> 00:04:49.920
With the green subsection of the bar showing that some patients achieved a complete response

00:04:49.920 --> 00:04:55.880
in approximately 46% of cases, they also did a subgroup analysis in patients with previous

00:04:55.880 --> 00:05:04.260
T-cell-directed therapy, and those patients also showed a favorable response with 32% achieving

00:05:04.260 --> 00:05:08.200
a complete response.

00:05:08.200 --> 00:05:14.400
Here is a dissection of how different patients did on the study.

00:05:14.400 --> 00:05:18.900
And the patients highlighted on the top in green are the ones that were able to achieve

00:05:18.900 --> 00:05:19.900
a complete response.

00:05:19.900 --> 00:05:25.800
And you can see that for the patients that did achieve a complete response with Jusqualcatamine-Rituximab,

00:05:25.800 --> 00:05:29.060
the response generally was durable.

00:05:29.060 --> 00:05:33.800
And unfortunately, there were some other patients that came off study due to progression of

00:05:33.800 --> 00:05:37.240
disease, infection, patient death, or investigator discretion.

00:05:37.240 --> 00:05:43.320
But for the patients that are able to achieve a response, they do have durable benefit.

00:05:43.320 --> 00:05:46.740
So in conclusion, Jusqualcatamine-Rituximab demonstrates promising efficacy in heavily

00:05:46.740 --> 00:05:51.240
pre-treated patients with relapsed refractory diffuse short-spaced lymphoma.

00:05:51.240 --> 00:05:55.180
For the patients that are able to achieve a durable response, this does provide some

00:05:55.180 --> 00:05:55.720
additional benefit.

00:05:55.720 --> 00:06:00.440
And it's rational for investigating its role in other settings, including the front-line

00:06:00.440 --> 00:06:01.440
setting.

00:06:01.440 --> 00:06:04.480
So this data supports the ongoing development of jusqualcatamine-Rituximab for patients in

00:06:04.480 --> 00:06:08.380
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, including in the Phase III GOAL-SEQ-1 study, which I'm participating

00:06:08.380 --> 00:06:12.820
in my institution, as well as the Phase III GOAL-SEQ-4 study in second-line follicular

00:06:12.820 --> 00:06:13.820
lymphoma.

00:06:13.820 --> 00:06:19.100
There are some other ongoing studies in which they're investigating its use prior to CAR-T

00:06:19.100 --> 00:06:22.400
as a bridging therapy, which I don't include here.

00:06:22.400 --> 00:06:25.640
But that's probably also another role that we'll see in the future.

00:06:25.640 --> 00:06:27.820
And so for that, I'll conclude my presentation.

00:06:27.820 --> 00:06:29.740
I'm open to questions or any discussion section.

00:06:29.740 --> 00:06:30.740
Thank you.
